\textbf{Question:} 
%TCIMACRO{\TeXButton{blueEnd}{\color[rgb]{0,0,0}}}%
%BeginExpansion
\color[rgb]{0,0,0}%
%EndExpansion
(10ed-10.1-6) Calculate $\int_{C}\mathbf{F}\cdot d\mathbf{r}$ for $\mathbf{F=%
}\left[ x-y,y-z,z-x\right] $ and $\mathbf{r=}\left[ 2\cos t,t,2\sin t\right] 
$ from $\left( 2,0,0\right) $ to $\left( 2,2\pi ,0\right) .$ Show the
details.

%TCIMACRO{\TeXButton{blue}{\color[rgb]{0,0,1}}}%
%BeginExpansion
\color[rgb]{0,0,1}%
%EndExpansion
\textbf{Solution:} 
%TCIMACRO{\TeXButton{blueEnd}{\color[rgb]{0,0,0}}}%
%BeginExpansion
\color[rgb]{0,0,0}%
%EndExpansion
We first find variation of $t:$ By putting $\mathbf{r=}\left[ 2\cos
t,t,2\sin t\right] =\left( 2,0,0\right) \Rightarrow t=0$ and $2\cos
t=2\Rightarrow t=2\pi .$ Validity of these values of $t$ may be checked by
putting final value of $t$ i.e. $2\pi $ and getting the terminal point,
already given to us i.e. $\left( 2,2\pi ,0\right) .$ Next we re-write $%
\mathbf{F}$ in terms of $t$ by using $x=2\cos t,y=t$ and $z=2\sin t$ into $%
\mathbf{F=}\left[ 2\cos t-t,t-2\sin t,2\sin t-2\cos t\right] .$ Hence 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\int_{C}\mathbf{F}\cdot d\mathbf{r} &\mathbf{=}&\int_{0}^{2\pi }\left( \left[
2\cos t-t,t-2\sin t,2\sin t-2\cos t\right] \cdot \frac{d}{dt}\left[ 2\cos
t,t,2\sin t\right] \right) dt \\
&=&\int_{0}^{2\pi }\left( \left[ 2\cos t-t,t-2\sin t,2\sin t-2\cos t\right]
\cdot \left[ -2\sin t,1,2\cos t\right] \right) dt \\
&=&\int_{0}^{2\pi }\left( t-2\sin t+2t\sin t-4\cos ^{2}t-4\cos t\sin t+4\sin
t\cos t\right) dt \\
&=&\int_{0}^{2\pi }\left( t-2\sin t-2\cos 2t+2t\sin t-2\right) dt \\
&=&2\pi \left( \pi -4\right)
\end{eqnarray*}%
