If $I=\int_{C}\left( 2xyz^{2}dx+\left( x^{2}z^{2}+z\cos \left( yz\right)
\right) dy+\left( 2x^{2}yz+y\cos \left( yz\right) \right) dz\right) $ is
path independent, then find its value from $A\left( 0,0,1\right) $ to $%
B\left( 1,\frac{\pi }{4},2\right) .$

%TCIMACRO{\TeXButton{blue}{\color[rgb]{0,0,1}}}%
%BeginExpansion
\color[rgb]{0,0,1}%
%EndExpansion
\textbf{Solution:} 
%TCIMACRO{\TeXButton{blueEnd}{\color[rgb]{0,0,0}}}%
%BeginExpansion
\color[rgb]{0,0,0}%
%EndExpansion
The question requires us to first establish the path independence of $I.$
For this we systematically find potential function $f\left( x,y,z\right) \ $%
as follows: we have%
\begin{equation*}
f_{x}=2xyz^{2},~~~f_{y}=x^{2}z^{2}+z\cos \left( yz\right)
,~~~f_{z}=2x^{2}yz+y\cos \left( yz\right)
\end{equation*}%
$\int f_{x}dx=\int 2xyz^{2}dx=\allowbreak x^{2}yz^{2}\Rightarrow
f=\allowbreak x^{2}yz^{2}+g\left( y,z\right) $

$f_{y}=g_{y}=x^{2}z^{2}+g_{y}=x^{2}z^{2}+z\cos \left( yz\right) \Rightarrow
\int g_{y}dy=\int z\cos \left( yz\right) dy=\allowbreak \sin yz+h\left(
z\right) \Rightarrow f=\allowbreak x^{2}yz^{2}+\sin yz+h\left( z\right) $

$f_{z}=\frac{d}{dz}\left( \allowbreak x^{2}yz^{2}+\sin yz\right)
=\allowbreak 2x^{2}yz+y\cos yz+h_{z}=2x^{2}yz+y\cos \left( yz\right)
\Rightarrow h_{z}=0$ i.e. $h\left( z\right) $ is constant, say $0.$ Hence we
have $f=\allowbreak x^{2}yz^{2}+\sin yz.$ As $\mathbf{F}$ is the gradient of 
$f=\allowbreak x^{2}yz^{2}+\sin yz$ hence the line integral may be evaluated
as%
\begin{eqnarray*}
&&\int_{\left( 0,0,1\right) }^{\left( 1,\frac{\pi }{4},2\right) }\left(
2xyz^{2}dx+\left( x^{2}z^{2}+z\cos \left( yz\right) \right) dy+\left(
2x^{2}yz+y\cos \left( yz\right) \right) dz\right) \\
&=&f\left( B\right) -f\left( A\right) =\left[ \allowbreak x^{2}yz^{2}+\sin yz%
\right] _{x=1,y=\frac{\pi }{4},z=2}-\left[ \allowbreak x^{2}yz^{2}+\sin yz%
\right] _{x=0,y=0,z=1} \\
&=&\left( \pi +1\right) -0=\pi +1~~~~~\blacksquare
\end{eqnarray*}

