(10ed-10.2-4) Show that the form under the integral $\int_{\left( 4,0\right)
}^{\left( 6,1\right) }e^{4y}\left( 2x~dx+4x^{2}~dy\right) $ is exact in the
plane and evaluate the integral. Show the details of your work?

%TCIMACRO{\TeXButton{blue}{\color[rgb]{0,0,1}}}%
%BeginExpansion
\color[rgb]{0,0,1}%
%EndExpansion
\textbf{Solution:} 
%TCIMACRO{\TeXButton{blueEnd}{\color[rgb]{0,0,0}}}%
%BeginExpansion
\color[rgb]{0,0,0}%
%EndExpansion
Here we have $F_{1}=2xe^{4y},F_{2}=4e^{4y}x^{2}$ and no third component.
Hence for exactness of the differential form we see $\frac{\partial F_{1}}{%
\partial y}=\frac{\partial }{\partial y}\left( 2xe^{4y}\right) =8xe^{4y}=%
\frac{\partial }{\partial x}\left( 4e^{4y}x^{2}\right) =\frac{\partial F_{2}%
}{\partial x},$ hence the form is exact and the integral is path
independent. So we may evaluate it by using its potential only i.e. $f.$ For
finding $f$ we set $f_{x}=2xe^{4y}$ and $f_{y}=4e^{4y}x^{2}.$ Now

$\int f_{x}dx=\int \left( 2xe^{4y}\right) dx=\allowbreak x^{2}e^{4y}+g\left(
y\right) \Rightarrow f=\allowbreak x^{2}e^{4y}+g\left( y\right) $ and $%
f_{y}=4x^{2}e^{4y}+g_{y}=4e^{4y}x^{2}\Rightarrow g\left( y\right) =0$ (say).
Potential is $f=x^{2}e^{4y}.$ Integral is computed as%
\begin{equation*}
\int_{\left( 4,0\right) }^{\left( 6,1\right) }e^{4y}\left(
2x~dx+4x^{2}~dy\right) =f\left( B\right) -f\left( A\right) =\left[
x^{2}e^{4y}\right] _{x=6,y=1}-\left[ x^{2}e^{4y}\right] _{x=4,y=0}=1949.\,%
\allowbreak 5~~~~~\blacksquare
\end{equation*}

