\section{Surfaces for Surface Integrals}

With line integrals, we integrate over curves in space, with surface
integrals we integrate over surfaces in space.Each curve in space is
represented by a parametric equation. This suggests that we should also find
parametric representations for the surfaces in space. As surfaces are two
dimensional objects, we need two parameters which we call $u$ and $v.$%
\begin{equation*}
\FRAME{itbpF}{2.9412in}{2.5642in}{0in}{}{}{Figure}{\special{language
"Scientific Word";type "GRAPHIC";maintain-aspect-ratio TRUE;display
"USEDEF";valid_file "T";width 2.9412in;height 2.5642in;depth
0in;original-width 5.9793in;original-height 5.2088in;cropleft "0";croptop
"1";cropright "1";cropbottom "0";tempfilename
'NPDIBO01.wmf';tempfile-properties "XPR";}}
\end{equation*}%
Thus \textbf{parametric representation} of a surface $S$ in space is of the
form%
\begin{equation*}
\mathbf{r}\left( u,v\right) =\left[ x\left( u,v\right) ,y\left( u,v\right)
,z\left( u,v\right) \right] =x\left( u,v\right) \mathbf{i}+y\left(
u,v\right) \mathbf{j}+z\left( u,v\right) \mathbf{k}
\end{equation*}%
where $\left( u,v\right) $ varies in some region $R$ of the $uv$-plane.

